lookup.term:
{Deposit}

          Any Context with deposited soil, eg natural deposits, floor and road surfaces and pit, ditch and grave fills

            {Natural}

{Coarse-grained_sediments}

          Soils with coarse-grained sediments such as gravel and sand.

            {Compact}

            Requires mattock for excavation.(MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Indurated}

            Broken only with sharp pick blow, even when soaked. (MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Loose}

            Can be excavated with hoe or trowel. (MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Strongly_cemented}

            Cannot be broken with hands. (MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Weakly_cemented}

            Pick removes sediment in lumps which can be broken with hands. (MoLAS 2004: 30)

{Fine-grained_sediments}

          Soils with fine-grained sediments such as silt and clay.

            {Friable}

            Non-plastic, crumbles in fingers.
          {Hard}

            Brittle or very tough. (MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Soft}

            Easily moulded with fingers.
          {Stiff}

            Cannot be moulded with fingers.(MoLAS 2004: 30)
          {Very_soft}

            Exudes between fingers when squeezed.

{Peat}

          Anaerobic accumulation of partially decayed vegetation.

            {Firm}

            Fibres compressed together. (MoLAS 1994: 30)
          {Plastic}

            Can be moulded in hands and smeared between fingers. (MoLAS 1994: 30)
          {Spongy}

            Very compressible and open structure. (MoLAS 1994: 30)

{Angular}

          Sharp pebbles or stones.

            {Angular}

            Sharp and pointed.
          {Sub-angular}

            A little sharp and pointed.
          {Very_angular}

            Very sharp and pointed.

{Rounded}

          Rounded stones and pebbles.

            {Rounded}

            Mostly rounded pebble or stone.
          {Sub-rounded}

            Some rounding to pebbles or stones.
          {Well-rounded}

            Very rounded pebble or stone.
